import json, os, sys

def load_comm(layer, book):
    path = f'data/commentary/mkt-{layer}/{book}.json'
    if os.path.exists(path):
        with open(path) as f:
            return json.load(f)
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    path = f'data/commentary/mkt-{layer}/{book}.json'
    os.makedirs(os.path.dirname(path), exist_ok=True)
    with open(path, 'w') as f:
        json.dump(data, f, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False)
    print(f'wrote {path}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

SAMUEL = {
    "13": {
        "1": "<p>The regnal formula for Saul — damaged in the MT with missing numerals (bracketed in most translations) — signals an editorial judgment rather than textual accident: Saul's reign defies clean summary. The broken formula anticipates the narrative's verdict that Saul's kingship was never fully established in the covenantal sense. Christ's reign by contrast is announced with precise coordinates (Luke 3:1–2) and governed by the Davidic covenant promise of an eternal throne (2 Sam 7:16; Luke 1:32–33).</p>",
        "2": "<p>Saul deploys 3,000 men in a defensive posture at Michmash and Bethel. The scale — 3,000 — is the same force Saul originally raised (1 Sam 11:8) but now deployed as a standing army. The institutional army was precisely what Samuel had warned about (8:11–12): a military apparatus requiring taxation and conscription. Saul's kingship is already becoming the machine Samuel predicted. Christ's kingdom does not advance by standing armies (John 18:36) but by the Spirit's power (Zech 4:6).</p>",
        "3": "<p>Jonathan's raid on the Philistine garrison at Geba initiates the crisis. Saul claims the trumpet-blast — the signal that YHWH is acting through Israel — but he claims it for himself rather than attributing it to Jonathan. The public announcement 'Saul has struck a Philistine garrison' appropriates Jonathan's victory. The dynamic of the powerful suppressing the achievement of the faithful subordinate contrasts with Christ, who attributes all glory to the Father (John 17:4) and honours those who serve him (John 12:26).</p>",
        "4": "<p>Israel has become 'repugnant' (MKT: <em>nibʾaš</em>, stinking, odious) to the Philistines — provoking a response that overwhelms Saul's capacity to resist. The verb is used for spoiled food (Ex 5:21; 2 Sam 10:6); Israel's covenant relationship with YHWH makes them a stench to their enemies. Paul picks up the same imagery positively: believers are 'the aroma of Christ to God' (2 Cor 2:15), deadly to some, life-giving to others. The nations' hostility to YHWH's people is a structural feature that Christ endured and conquered (John 15:18–19).</p>",
        "5": "<p>The Philistine mobilisation — 30,000 chariots, 6,000 cavalry, 'as numerous as the sand on the seashore' — is described in the hyperbolic vocabulary of overwhelming force. The chariot count may reflect scribal error (LXX reads 3,000), but the narrative effect is intentional: Israel faces an existential threat they cannot match. The 'sand of the seashore' (Gen 22:17) is the language of covenant promise applied now as the vocabulary of military threat — the same imagery used for YHWH's blessings now quantifies the enemy. Christ faced the accumulated power of sin, death, and demonic opposition, and prevailed where no human king could.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The troops hide in caves, thickets, rocks, tombs, and cisterns — the landscape of the underworld in Israelite imagination. <em>bôr</em> (cistern, pit) is also the term for Sheol in Psalms; the men of Israel are symbolically descending into death. The scene of a people in hiding from overwhelming force anticipates the disciples' locked-room fear after the crucifixion (John 20:19). Christ descended into death itself (Eph 4:9; 1 Pet 3:18–20) and emerged victorious, enabling his followers to come out of hiding as witnesses (Acts 1:8).</p>",
        "7": "<p>Some Hebrews flee across the Jordan into Gad and Gilead — beyond Israel's borders, into the wilderness east of the river. The Jordan crossing as an act of fearful retreat inverts the original Joshua crossing (Josh 3–4) that brought Israel into the land. The original Jordan crossing was into promise; this one is flight from responsibility. Saul remains at Gilgal — the site of Israel's first covenant renewal after the Jordan (Josh 4:19–20) — trembling. Gilgal should be a place of faith; it becomes a place of paralysis.</p>",
        "9": "<p>Saul commands the burnt offering and fellowship offerings to be brought — acting as officiant at sacrifices reserved for the Aaronic priesthood or for occasions when Samuel was present (cf. 1 Sam 10:8). The act of offering sacrifice was a priestly prerogative; kings in Israel were explicitly separated from the priestly office (2 Chr 26:16–21 records the same violation by Uzziah). Saul's usurpation of the priestly role is the structural error: he conflates kingship and priesthood in an unlawful way. Christ alone legitimately holds both offices — as king of Melchizedek's order, in whom priest and king are united by divine appointment (Heb 7:1–3; Ps 110:1–4).</p>",
        "10": "<p>Samuel arrives the moment Saul finishes the offering. The timing is the theological point: Saul's act of faithless sacrifice was unnecessary. One more moment of trust would have solved the problem that his fear could not. Samuel's arrival immediately after the sacrifice is not narrative coincidence but the narrator's judgment: faith would have been rewarded had it lasted. Christ's resurrection after three days uses the same economy of redemptive timing — the wait was precisely long enough to establish the reality of death before the reversal.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Saul's defence — 'I saw the people scattering, you didn't come when you said you would, the Philistines were assembling' — lists three external pressures as the explanation for his action. Each is an accurate description of his circumstances; none is an adequate excuse for transgressing the divine command. The pattern is Adam's defence (Gen 3:12: 'the woman you gave me'): circumstances become the explanation for disobedience. Christ, facing infinitely greater pressure in Gethsemane (Matt 26:38–39), held to the Father's will despite circumstances that made abandonment humanly rational.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'I felt forced to offer the burnt offering.' The passive construction 'felt forced' (<em>hiṯʾappaqqtî</em>, I constrained/forced myself) is Saul's self-presentation as reluctant actor rather than wilful rebel. He is not lying about his internal state — he genuinely felt compelled. But the NT diagnoses the same dynamic in Gal 6:12: people who do things 'to make a good showing in the flesh' or to avoid persecution are not lying about their motives; their motives themselves have been corrupted by fear. Saul's compulsion was real; the compulsion itself was the sin.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Samuel's verdict: 'You have acted foolishly' (<em>nisbāltā</em>). The verb <em>sāḵal</em> in the Niphal means to act without understanding, to be a fool — not merely stupid but covenantally ignorant (Ps 14:1, 'the fool says there is no God'). Saul has not kept the commandment of YHWH his God. The sentence is judicial and final: the kingdom would have been established forever for Saul's line, but now it will not endure. The conditional eternal covenant (with Saul) is terminated by disobedience in exactly the structure that Deuteronomy promised (Deut 28:1–2; 15–16).</p>",
        "15": "<p>Samuel departs; Saul counts his men and finds 600. From 3,000 (v2) to 600 is a catastrophic desertion rate of 80%. The remaining 600 echo the 600 who camped with the Danites (Judg 18:11) and the 600 who fled to Rimmon in the Gibeah war (Judg 20:47) — a militarily desperate minimum. In Gideon's narrative, YHWH reduced 32,000 to 300 to demonstrate that salvation belongs to YHWH (Judg 7:7); here the reduction to 600 is the result of Saul's failure, not divine staging. The remnant who remain will need Jonathan's faith rather than Saul's army.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Saul and Jonathan are at Gibeah of Benjamin while the Philistines camp at Michmash — occupying the heights between them. The geographical configuration establishes a military standoff mirroring Judg 17–18's Gibeah (the site of the concubine's abuse) and the earlier Gibeah stories. Gibeah's geography is contested space throughout Samuel; its association with Benjamin's worst episode (Judg 19–20) shadows Saul's identity as a Benjaminite king whose failure will echo Gibeah's moral collapse.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Three Philistine raiding parties move in three directions — Ophrah (north), Beth-horon (west), and the Zeboim valley (east/southeast). The tripartite deployment is a classic flanking manoeuvre designed to cut off retreat and pillage the surrounding territory simultaneously. The raids are not conquest but economic devastation: the purpose is to reduce Israel's capacity to sustain resistance. The systematic economic pressure on a people waiting for their king to act is another dimension of Saul's failure to act after Jonathan's initiative.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The three raiding parties establish Philistine dominance over the central hill country approaches. The location names — Beth-horon, Zeboim, the wilderness — trace the boundaries of Benjamin's tribal territory. The Philistines are not just attacking Israel in general but specifically decimating the Benjaminite heartland from which Saul himself comes. The king who cannot protect his own tribal territory is already functionally deposed. The protective shepherd who abandons his sheep contrasts with Christ the Good Shepherd who lays down his life rather than abandoning the flock (John 10:11–12).</p>",
        "19": "<p>No metalworker in all Israel: 'the Philistines had said, otherwise the Hebrews will make swords or spears.' The iron-monopoly is a documented feature of Philistine domination in the Iron Age I period; archaeology confirms their iron superiority (Tell Qasile, Gezer calendar). Theologically, the detail explains why Jonathan's faith-initiative in ch14 is the only viable strategy: conventional military power is structurally unavailable. Israel must act with the weapons YHWH provides. Paul's spiritual warfare passage (Eph 6:10–18) addresses the same structural disadvantage — believers facing powers who control conventional force must use divine armour.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Every Israelite had to go to Philistia for basic agricultural tool maintenance — plowshares, mattocks, axes, sickles. The dependency is total: even civilian life (farming) requires Philistine permission. The agricultural implements listed are the tools of peaceful production; their sharpening at enemy cost makes every harvest a tribute payment. Christ liberates from the kind of comprehensive economic/spiritual bondage described here: 'For freedom Christ has set us free; do not submit again to a yoke of slavery' (Gal 5:1).</p>",
        "21": "<p>The pricing in thirds and two-thirds of a shekel represents the ANE standard for blade-sharpening services; the detail grounds the narrative in economic reality. The cost of maintaining basic tools — not luxury items but agricultural necessities — was extracted by the dominant power. The structural dependence of the occupied on the occupier for the most basic necessities describes a comprehensive captivity. The NT's language of ransom (<em>lutrōsis</em>) and redemption (<em>apolutrōsis</em>) addresses exactly this kind of total-cost bondage (Titus 2:14; Heb 9:12).</p>",
        "22": "<p>'Not one soldier in Saul and Jonathan's force had a sword or spear — only Saul and Jonathan.' The exception that arms the two leaders while the soldiers are unarmed is a measure of the monopoly's effectiveness: the army cannot arm itself. The military context for ch14's initiative makes Jonathan's faith-exploit more remarkable: he goes into combat with no sword for his armor-bearer. David's sling over Goliath's spear (1 Sam 17) is the theological continuation: YHWH does not need conventional weapons to save (1 Sam 17:47). The weapon of the cross is foolishness to those who think in terms of conventional force (1 Cor 1:18).</p>",
        "23": "<p>The Philistine garrison occupies the pass of Michmash — the natural chokepoint in the Benjamin highlands (modern Mukhmas). Controlling the pass is the militarily decisive position; it cuts Israel's forces in two and prevents Jonathan's raiders from operating freely. Jonathan's initiative in ch14 will target this garrison directly, demonstrating that the seemingly decisive terrain advantage can be overcome when YHWH fights. The 'narrow pass' (<em>maʿbār</em>) that the Philistines hold becomes the site of Israel's deliverance — narrow places of difficulty become places of salvation throughout scripture (Ps 18:19).</p>"
    },
    "14": {
        "1": "<p>Jonathan's proposal — 'let us cross over to the Philistine garrison on the other side' — comes without consulting his father. The unilateral initiative is the narrative's first sign that the Spirit-driven energy in Saul's army has migrated from father to son. Jonathan's faith-action will contrast with Saul's paralysis throughout ch14. Christ's own initiative — 'No one takes my life from me; I lay it down of my own accord' (John 10:18) — is the ultimate model of the Spirit-driven servant who acts from divine impulse rather than institutional permission.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Saul is 'stationed at the edge of Gibeah under the pomegranate tree at Migron.' The pomegranate tree is a detail of pastoral tranquility; the king sitting under it while his son crosses to the enemy describes a leader at rest while danger presses. Saul's 600 men — the remnant of 3,000 (13:2, 15) — represent his diminished capacity. The 'edge of Gibeah' places him at the border between the known and unknown; his position is liminal but passive. Contrast with the Servant of Isaiah who 'set his face like flint' toward Jerusalem (Isa 50:7) and Christ who 'resolutely set out for Jerusalem' (Luke 9:51).</p>",
        "3": "<p>Ahijah son of Ahitub — 'the LORD's priest at Shiloh, wearing an ephod' — is the institutional priestly presence with Saul. His lineage traces directly to Eli: grandson of Phinehas, great-grandson of Eli, the priest under whom the ark was lost. The priestly line associated with Shiloh's failure (1 Sam 2:27–36) accompanies the king destined to fail. Christ's priesthood is not traced through failed priestly dynasties but appointed directly: 'You are a priest forever after the order of Melchizedek' (Ps 110:4; Heb 5:5–6), bypassing the Aaronic succession entirely.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The two rocky crags — Bozez ('shining') and Seneh ('thorny') — that flank the pass of Michmash are named for the reader, emphasising their strategic formidability. Two sheer faces guarding a mountain pass is a military obstacle that professional analysis would declare impassable. Jonathan's plan to climb one of them with his armor-bearer is precisely the irrational act that faith enables. The NT logic is identical: 'God chose what is foolish in the world to shame the wise; God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong' (1 Cor 1:27).</p>",
        "5": "<p>The directional identification of the crags — north toward Michmash, south toward Gibeah — gives the reader the spatial orientation needed to understand Jonathan's climbing route. The geography is precise; the narrator records it to ground the miraculous in the real: this is a specific identifiable terrain feature in the Benjamin highlands, not a mythological landscape. The incarnation similarly grounds the salvific act in specific geography and history (Luke 2:1–4; 3:1–2) — the God who saves acts in a particular place and time.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The armor-bearer's reply — 'Do whatever is in your heart; I am with you, whatever you decide' — is one of the most complete expressions of covenantal loyalty in Samuel. The phrase 'whatever is in your heart' (<em>kol-ašer billibḇəḵā</em>) is the language of whole-hearted commitment (cf. 2 Sam 7:3, Nathan's initial response to David's temple-plan). The armor-bearer does not know the outcome; he commits unconditionally to Jonathan's initiative. This anticipates the disciples' unconditional commitment (Matt 16:24; John 11:16), which is itself a reflection of Christ's own unconditional obedience to the Father (Phil 2:8).</p>",
        "8": "<p>'We will cross over to them and let ourselves be seen.' Jonathan's strategy involves deliberate vulnerability: exposing themselves to the enemy's observation rather than approaching under cover. The plan inverts normal military logic — concealment is survival, visibility is death. Jonathan is using his own exposure as the mechanism for the sign from YHWH (vv9–10). Christ's own visibility — his public entry into Jerusalem (John 12:12–15), his refusal to hide or escape Gethsemane (John 18:4–5) — is the same pattern of deliberate exposure that enables rather than prevents salvation.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The negative sign: if they say 'stay there until we come to you,' that means YHWH has not given them into Jonathan's hand. The contingency plan is not retreat-as-failure but obedient waiting: a real word from YHWH that says 'not now' is as valid as a word that says 'go.' Jonathan's faith includes the possibility that YHWH may withhold deliverance at this moment. This is the faith of Gethsemane: 'Yet not my will but yours' (Luke 22:42) — which contemplates the possibility of the cup not being removed while remaining in faith.</p>",
        "10": "<p>'Come up to us — that will be our sign that the LORD has handed them over to us.' The positive sign turns an enemy taunt into divine confirmation. The Philistines' arrogant invitation ('come up here and we'll show you something') will become, in Jonathan's interpretive framework, the word of YHWH authorising the assault. Reading the enemy's contemptuous challenge as divine invitation is the theology of the cross: what the world sees as defeat and mockery (1 Cor 1:23), faith reads as the ordained mechanism of salvation.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'Look — the Hebrews are crawling out of the holes they've been hiding in.' The Philistine contempt articulates exactly the condition described in 13:6 — Israel hiding in caves and cisterns. Their mockery is accurate: Jonathan and his armor-bearer have emerged from hiding to approach. The contempt of the powerful toward the weak is the precondition for the reversal; God specifically chooses the despised to shame those who think themselves powerful (1 Cor 1:28). The taunt about crawling out of holes becomes the occasion for YHWH's action.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'Come on up — we will show you something!' The invitation is contemptuous, and Jonathan immediately reads it as the positive sign. His response to his armor-bearer — 'follow me, for the LORD has given them into Israel's hand' — makes the interpretive move explicit: he has received the word of YHWH in the enemy's taunt. The certainty is prophetic, not strategic; Jonathan knows the outcome before the battle begins. This is the faith of Heb 11:1 — 'the certainty of things not seen' — taking the form of strategic action based on divine word rather than human calculation.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Jonathan scrambles up on his hands and feet — an undignified climbing posture that emphasises the physical difficulty of the approach. The Philistines fall before him 'in the presence of his armor-bearer' (<em>weʾaḥărāyw haśśilāḥ nōpēl</em>). The passive grammatical framing of the Philistine deaths (they fall) vs. the active verbs of Jonathan's advance (he climbed, he struck) underlines that the agency is Jonathan's in battle but YHWH's in determination. Christ's passion narratives show the same double agency: the soldiers arrest him (John 18:12), but 'no one takes my life from me' (John 10:18).</p>",
        "14": "<p>Twenty men killed 'in about half an acre' — the MKT's 'half an acre' renders the Hebrew <em>ḵamaʿănāh semeth śāḏeh</em>, a unit of roughly the area a yoke of oxen plows in a day. The spatial confinement emphasises that this was not a running battle but a focused engagement in a small area. The number twenty is small but the effect is decisive: it triggers the divine panic that spreads through the entire Philistine camp (v15). Small acts of faith-obedience at the narrow pass of YHWH's appointment have disproportionate effects in the kingdom of God (Matt 13:31–33).</p>",
        "15": "<p>Terror spreads through the whole Philistine force — 'camp, field, garrison, and raiding parties alike. The ground shook — it was a divine panic.' The phrase <em>ḥaradat ʾĕlōhîm</em> ('divine panic,' 'panic from God') is the technical term for the theophanic fear that strikes armies when YHWH acts directly (Ex 14:24; Josh 10:10; 1 Sam 7:10). The earthquake reinforces the theophanic character: YHWH is present in the battle. Jonathan's twenty casualties did not cause 30,000 Philistines to flee; the divine panic did. The faithful act opened the space for YHWH's power.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Saul's sentries observe the Philistine camp 'disintegrating — men rushing about this way and that.' The scene is observed from a distance; Saul is still under his pomegranate tree. He hears about the victory before he participates in it; Jonathan has already broken the impasse without Saul's involvement. The king who should have led is informed after the fact. Christ is never the passive observer of his own redemptive mission; he is its initiator and agent (Heb 12:2, 'the founder and perfecter of our faith').</p>",
        "17": "<p>Saul's response to the intelligence is to take a roll call — checking who is missing rather than immediately joining the battle. The administrative instinct to count before acting is another marker of Saul's cautious institutional leadership. The roll call reveals Jonathan's absence — Saul did not know his son had crossed to the Philistine garrison. The discovery that Jonathan acted without authorisation is more significant than the discovery that Jonathan won; Saul's subsequent oath (v24) will try to re-impose authority over an event he didn't control.</p>",
        "18": "<p>Saul calls for the ark of God. The parenthetical note 'the ark of God was with Israel at that time' reminds the reader that the ark, recovered from Philistine captivity after the Ichabod incident (chs 4–6), is again in Israelite hands. Consulting the ark in battle was proper theophanic procedure; Saul is attempting to use the institutional sacred object to validate his joining of a battle his son has already decided. The contrast between the ark being consulted post-hoc and YHWH actually acting through Jonathan's prior initiative captures the gap between institutional religion and living faith.</p>",
        "19": "<p>While Saul consults the priest, the Philistine uproar grows louder. Saul's impatience — 'withdraw your hand' (i.e., stop the consultation) — cuts off the priestly inquiry he has just initiated. He cannot wait for a divine answer even in the act of seeking one. The half-consulted oracle and the abandoned inquiry mark Saul as a man who uses religion as a tool rather than actually seeking YHWH's guidance. The short attention span of self-directed prayer contrasts with Christ's sustained communion with the Father (Luke 6:12; Mark 1:35; John 17).</p>",
        "20": "<p>'They found every Philistine's sword turned against his own companion.' YHWH's direct action in the Philistine camp produces internecine killing — the enemy destroys itself. This is the pattern of Gideon's night attack (Judg 7:22) and Jehoshaphat's battle (2 Chr 20:23), where YHWH causes the enemy to fight each other. The theological point is consistent: when YHWH intervenes, the enemy's own power becomes its weapon against itself. Sin ultimately destroys the sinner; the powers arrayed against God's purposes become instruments of their own defeat (1 Cor 15:25–26).</p>",
        "21": "<p>Hebrews who had been serving with the Philistines switch sides 'when they heard YHWH was with Israel.' The defection of former collaborators to YHWH's side when victory becomes apparent is a recurring pattern in holy war narratives (cf. Rahab, Josh 2). The question of identity — who are YHWH's people? — is answered pragmatically: those who attach themselves to YHWH's saving action are incorporated. The eschatological version is Rev 7:9, the great multitude from every nation gathered around the Lamb — former outsiders incorporated into the victory.</p>",
        "22": "<p>Hidden Israelites from the hill country of Ephraim come out to join the pursuit. The image of a dispersed, hiding population coming out when YHWH acts recalls the scattered Diaspora gathering (Isa 11:12; 27:12–13; Zeph 3:20). The scattered people who could not act while the enemy was dominant now join the victory already won. The church's mission in Acts follows the same pattern: people scattered by persecution become witnesses (Acts 8:4); those who were hiding become emboldened by the Spirit's action (Acts 4:13, 31).</p>",
        "23": "<p>'The LORD saved Israel that day.' The summary statement uses <em>yayyôšaʿ</em> (Hiphil of <em>yāšaʿ</em>: YHWH caused salvation), the same root as Yeshua/Jesus. The day's salvation is explicitly credited to YHWH, not to Jonathan's courage or Saul's military organisation. The gospel declaration 'the LORD saved Israel that day' is the prototype for 'the LORD saved the world that day' — the eschatological salvation secured at the cross (John 12:31; 1 John 4:14, 'the Father sent the Son to be the Savior of the world').</p>",
        "24": "<p>Saul's rash oath — 'Cursed be anyone who eats food before evening before I take vengeance on my enemies' — imposes a collective fast on the exhausted troops in the middle of battle. The oath is structurally identical to Jephthah's vow (Judg 11:30–31): a conditional self-curse that attempts to leverage YHWH's blessing by self-imposed hardship. Both oaths produce unintended harm to innocent parties. Saul uses the mechanism of curse-binding to re-establish his authority over a victory he didn't initiate. The NT warns against oaths that bind where they should not (Matt 5:33–37).</p>",
        "25": "<p>Honey flowing on the ground — a detail of natural abundance (Deut 8:8, the land of 'honey flowing in the brooks') in the middle of a battle. The forest produces what the covenant land promises; the troops are surrounded by sweetness they cannot access because of Saul's oath. The land flows with milk and honey for the covenant people, but Saul's fear-driven prohibition prevents them from receiving what YHWH has provided. Leaders who restrict rather than enable access to covenantal blessing are a recurring figure of failed leadership throughout the prophets (Ezek 34:1–6).</p>",
        "26": "<p>The honey is 'flowing freely' but 'no one lifted his hand to his mouth because of the oath.' The collective restraint under oath — even in the face of freely available refreshment — shows the power of the binding curse. The people are famished (v28), the honey is there, the battle requires strength, and yet the oath holds them back. The constraint is not covenantal obedience (YHWH never commanded the fast) but Saul's self-willed curse. The distinction between YHWH's commands (which give life, Deut 30:19) and human-imposed burdens (which crush) is the contrast between law as gift and law as yoke (Matt 11:28–30; Gal 5:1).</p>",
        "28": "<p>The soldier who informs Jonathan about the oath adds: 'the troops are exhausted.' The physical depletion is the practical consequence of Saul's oath: YHWH provided a decisive military victory but Saul's self-willed fasting policy prevented the troops from capitalising on it. Jonathan's response (v29) draws the logical conclusion: the people would have killed even more Philistines if they had been allowed to eat. Leadership that depletes its followers through unnecessary restrictions undermines the mission. Christ, by contrast, feeds the exhausted who follow him (Mark 6:31–44; 8:1–9).</p>",
        "29": "<p>'My father has brought trouble on the land (<em>ʿāḵar</em>).' The verb <em>ʿāḵar</em> (to trouble, to bring disaster) is the same used for Achan's sin at Jericho (Josh 7:25) and Jephthah's daughter (Judg 11:35). Jonathan uses it for his father's rash oath: the oath has 'troubled Israel' in the same way Achan's covenant violation troubled Israel — creating a barrier between the people and covenantal blessing. Jonathan's see-how-much-better response ('see how my eyes brightened from tasting this honey') is empirical evidence that the oath was counterproductive, not covenantally required.</p>",
        "30": "<p>Jonathan's military analysis is strategically sound: if the troops had eaten from the plunder, the slaughter would have been greater. He is right on both counts — the exhaustion cost military effectiveness, and the oath was not from YHWH. The tragedy of Saul's reign is that he has correct military instincts (13:2, deploying a standing army; 14:36, pursuing the Philistines) but his fear-driven decisions consistently undermine the very goals he pursues. The self-defeating leader who sabotages his own mission through self-protective decisions is the foil to Christ's self-giving that produces abundant life (John 10:10).</p>",
        "31": "<p>The troops drive the Philistines from Michmash to Aijalon — a distance of roughly 30km — and are 'utterly exhausted.' Aijalon is the valley where the sun stood still for Joshua's victory (Josh 10:12–13); the same territory sees another great Philistine rout, but exhausted rather than fortified troops accomplish it. The geographical connection to Joshua's victory at Aijalon underlines what has been lost by the oath: the battle could have had the scale and completeness of Joshua's campaigns. Saul's oath transformed a decisive Josuah-style victory into an exhausted partial rout.</p>",
        "32": "<p>The troops 'swooped on the plunder... and slaughtered animals on the ground, eating with the blood.' The covenantal violation (eating blood — Lev 17:10–14; Gen 9:4) is the direct consequence of Saul's oath: starving men eating hastily slaughtered animals violate the blood law. One rash oath produces a second violation. The cascading effects of Saul's self-willed restrictions show how unauthorised religious regulation creates the very sins it purports to prevent. Legalism produces antinomianism; the grace of Christ which gives adequate nourishment prevents the desperation that drives violation (John 6:35).</p>",
        "33": "<p>Saul's response to the blood-eating report — 'You have broken faith! Roll a great stone to me now!' — is decisive crisis management of the immediate problem. He builds an improvised altar and implements the proper blood-draining procedure. But the crisis is of his own making: the oath created the hunger, the hunger created the violation. Saul addresses the symptom with proper ritual while remaining blind to the disease. The prophetic indictment of leaders who manage religious symptoms while creating the structural conditions for sin finds its NT parallel in Christ's confrontation of the Pharisees (Matt 23:23–24).</p>",
        "34": "<p>Saul's instruction — 'bring your ox and sheep here, slaughter them here, and eat; do not sin against the LORD by eating with the blood' — restores proper covenant practice. The king who created the crisis now resolves it by proper instruction. The solution is exactly what it should be (proper blood-draining before eating), but the fact that it was needed at all is Saul's failure. The NT's diagnostic insight is that addressing behavioral violations without addressing heart conditions (the source of the oath) produces compliance without transformation (Matt 15:17–20).</p>",
        "35": "<p>'Saul built an altar to the LORD — the first altar he ever built to the LORD.' The narrator's note is damning: after years as king, this is his first altar. An altar represents a site of regular communion with YHWH; Saul had been king (and fighting, and sacrificing in violation of priestly rules) without ever constructing a regular worship site. The contrast with David — who builds an altar at the threshing floor of Araunah (2 Sam 24:18–25) and whose final act before death is preparing for the temple — is stark. Worship is the expression of a heart that knows its dependence on YHWH; Saul had the actions but not the heart (1 Sam 15:22).</p>",
        "36": "<p>Saul proposes a night raid on the Philistines; the priest suggests consulting God first. This is the correct order (seek YHWH, then act), and Saul agrees. But the response from YHWH is silence — the sign that something is blocking covenantal communication. The priest's suggestion embodies the Levitical theology of consultation before action (Num 27:21); Saul's willingness to consult here contrasts with his earlier abandonment of consultation (v19). The silence of God in response to Saul's inquiry is one of the most sobering moments in Samuel: YHWH does not answer because there is sin in the camp. Blocked prayer (Isa 59:2; 1 Pet 3:7) signals a relational problem that requires resolution.</p>",
        "37": "<p>God does not answer Saul. The unanswered prayer is not divine absence but divine communication — the silence itself is the answer. YHWH is present and attentive but refuses to respond until the obstacle is identified. The structure anticipates Achan's lot-casting (Josh 7:16–18): undiscovered covenant violation blocks corporate access to divine guidance. The NT principle of 'if I had cherished sin in my heart, the Lord would not have listened' (Ps 66:18) and Christ's warning about settling matters before prayer (Matt 5:23–24) address the same dynamic: unresolved sin blocks communion.</p>",
        "38": "<p>'Come here, all you leaders of the army. Let us find out where the sin lies.' Saul frames the investigation correctly — the unanswered prayer indicates sin, and the community must identify it. The administrative procedure (gather the leaders, conduct an inquiry) is appropriate. But Saul does not suspect himself or his oath; he is looking for someone else's violation. The self-exculpating investigator who prosecutes others while remaining blind to his own guilt is the figure of the plank-and-speck passage (Matt 7:3–5) and the Pharisee's prayer (Luke 18:11).</p>",
        "39": "<p>'As the LORD who delivers Israel lives — even if the guilt lies with Jonathan my own son, he will certainly die.' The oath sworn by YHWH's name makes the self-curse legally absolute in Israelite covenant law; invoking the divine name as surety forecloses human commutation. Saul does not suspect Jonathan, and his inclusion of Jonathan is probably rhetorical — the king demonstrating impartial justice. But the irony is total: the very person who 'delivered Israel' (v45, <em>yaśāh yəšûʿāh gəḏôlāh</em>, 'worked this great deliverance') is the person under the death sentence.</p>",
        "40": "<p>Saul and Jonathan stand on one side; all the people on the other. The binary casting — two against all — prepares for the lot to identify one of the two rather than one of the many. The people agree: 'Do what seems right to you.' The public consent to the lot mechanism legitimises the process. The paradox that the lot will fall on Jonathan — YHWH's agent of that day's salvation — is the mechanism by which YHWH will expose the contradiction between Saul's oath and YHWH's actual will. The unjust verdict on the just person is the prelude to intercession (v45).</p>",
        "41": "<p>'Give a true decision' (<em>tāmîm</em>, 'completeness, integrity') — Saul's prayer for the lot is technically correct: he asks for the lot to reveal the truth. The LXX preserves a longer prayer that explicitly lists the Urim and Thummim mechanism. The lot falls on Saul and Jonathan rather than the people — narrowing the field. The people 'were cleared' (<em>wayyēṣeʾ hāʿām</em>, 'the people went out'). The progressive narrowing — all Israel → Saul+Jonathan → Jonathan alone — is the forensic procedure of holy war investigation (cf. Josh 7:16–18), applying covenantal forensic logic to the identification of guilt.</p>",
        "42": "<p>'Cast between me and Jonathan.' The final lot falls on Jonathan. The mechanism has correctly identified the person who violated (unknowingly) the oath — but the knowledge that Jonathan did not know of the oath transforms the verdict from justice to tragedy. The lot mechanism is reliable (Prov 16:33: 'the lot is cast into the lap, but its every decision is from the LORD'); what it reveals is the structural injustice of Saul's oath, not Jonathan's personal guilt. The lot exposes Saul's error even while technically condemning Jonathan. YHWH's truth-mechanisms vindicate the innocent even when they initially appear to convict them (cf. Job).</p>",
        "43": "<p>Jonathan's confession — 'I tasted a little honey with the tip of my staff; here I am, I will die' — is the most nobly understated moment in the chapter. He does not protest his innocence, appeal to ignorance, or beg for mercy. His 'here I am' (<em>hinnēnî</em>) is the same word of obedient availability used by Abraham at the binding of Isaac (Gen 22:1, 7, 11) and by Isaiah at his commissioning (Isa 6:8). Jonathan's 'here I am, I will die' is innocent obedience to a process that has found against him; it anticipates Christ's 'Not my will but yours' in Gethsemane (Luke 22:42).</p>",
        "44": "<p>'May God punish me severely if you do not die, Jonathan.' Saul's death-sentence is the mechanical application of his own oath; he is not exercising personal vengeance but invoking the covenant curse he himself established (v39). But the death-sentence on the day's deliverer is a legal injustice that the community will not allow to stand (v45). The structural parallel with Christ is precise: the legal mechanism (Roman law + Jewish law) condemned the one who came to save, and the execution was carried out — but death could not hold the one whom YHWH vindicated (Acts 2:24; Rom 8:34).</p>",
        "46": "<p>Saul calls off the Philistine pursuit after Jonathan's redemption. The night raid — which could have completed the day's rout — is abandoned. Another incomplete victory: the day that began with Jonathan's faith-exploit and YHWH's intervention ends with Saul's oath entangling the army, exhausted troops, blood-eating violation, and the near-execution of the day's hero. The Philistines 'return to their own territory' undefeated. Saul's accumulated self-willed decisions have converted a YHWH-given rout into a tactical draw. The squandered victory becomes a parable of leadership that fails to steward what YHWH provides.</p>",
        "47": "<p>The summary of Saul's reign — fighting Moab, Ammon, Edom, Zobah, Philistines, Amalekites — catalogues his external military activity. He 'achieved success wherever he turned.' The summary appears positive but functions as a foil: external military success without internal covenantal faithfulness is the precise diagnosis of the king the people requested (8:20, 'fight our battles for us'). They got what they asked for — a battle-fighter — but the covenant king requires more than military competence. Christ fulfils both dimensions: the victorious warrior (Rev 19:11–16) and the covenant mediator (Heb 9:15).</p>",
        "48": "<p>Saul struck the Amalekites and 'rescued Israel from those who had been plundering them.' The word 'rescued' (<em>wayyaṣṣel</em>, Hiphil of <em>nāṣal</em>) is the standard salvific verb; Saul performs the deliverer's function. But the Amalekite campaign will return in ch15 as the occasion of Saul's final rejection: his incomplete obedience in that campaign will cost him the kingdom. The partial salvation — rescue from immediate plunder without full covenantal obedience — describes a kingdom that delivers from external enemies while failing internal covenant tests. Christ's salvation is complete: 'It is finished' (John 19:30).</p>",
        "49": "<p>The genealogical note on Saul's family — Jonathan, Ishvi (perhaps Ish-bosheth), Malchishua; daughters Merab and Michal — grounds the narrative in the dynastic reality Saul is building. The sons who will die with him at Gilboa (1 Sam 31:2) are named here at the height of his power. The daughters whose marriages will intersect with David (Merab given to Adriel, 18:19; Michal given to David, 18:27) are also present. The dynastic family list is the human apparatus of the kingdom YHWH is about to transfer; it will not endure in the form Saul intends.</p>",
        "50": "<p>Saul's wife Ahinoam and his army commander Abner son of Ner — the institutional apparatus of a functional monarchy. Abner's relationship to Saul (his uncle) places the military command within the family, a standard ANE practice for ensuring loyalty. But Abner will survive Saul and become the military broker who tries to preserve Ishbosheth's claim against David (2 Sam 2:8–3:27) — the instrument of the attempt to perpetuate Saul's dynasty after its rejection. The supporting cast of human institutions outlasts the king they served, seeking to preserve what YHWH has already transferred.</p>",
        "51": "<p>Kish and Ner, Saul's and Abner's fathers, are identified as sons of Abiel. The tribal genealogy establishes the Benjaminite connections of the military household; it also places both the king and his general within the same extended family. The concentration of royal and military power in a single kin network is the institutional consolidation of Saul's reign. The NT pattern reverses this: Christ's kingdom is not a kin-network of the powerful but a community gathered across every ethnicity and kinship (Gal 3:28; Rev 5:9–10).</p>",
        "52": "<p>'War with the Philistines was fierce throughout Saul's reign.' The closing verse of the chapter's narrative summary frames Saul's entire reign under the sign of irresolution: the Philistine threat that dominated chs 13–14 is not permanently resolved. Saul 'enlisted capable or courageous men' — building a professional army — but the Philistine problem will only be solved by David, who dispatches them at Baal-perazim (2 Sam 5:20) after being anointed king. The irresolvable external threat under the inadequate king will be resolved by the king after YHWH's own heart — pointing forward to Christ who resolves permanently what human leadership cannot (Rom 8:37–39).</p>"
    }
}

